<paragraph id="5B093630FFC9EF79C4F5F897FF70F82D" blockId="10.[151,1436,1839,2009]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Known only from two females, this species is unusual in having the body extensively pale but the fore wings uniformly brown. The antenna is relatively short (
<figureCitation id="C38D2AB5FFC9EF79C6CAF8F2FCA8F8CE" box="[680,779,1876,1900]" captionStart="FIGURES 93 – 101" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1821,1844]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1799]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,193,1800]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 93 – 101. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. striatus female 93 – 96: 93. Dorsal view; 94. Antenna; 95. Mesonotum and metanotum; 96. Pronotum. H. brasiliensis female 97 – 100: 97. Dorsal view; 98. Antenna; 99. Head and pronotum; 100. Mesonotum and metanotum. H. flavidus female: 101. Antenna." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280422/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Fig. 
<number id="ED7E2417FFC9EF79C6BCF8F2FCA8F8CE" box="[734,779,1876,1900]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="101.0">101</number>
</figureCitation>
), and the pronotum is moderately closely striate with pale lines.
</paragraph>
